{"title_page": "Conestoga High School", "text_new": "{{peacock|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Conestoga High School\n | seal_image              = StogaLogo.png\n | seal_size               = \n | image                   = Conestoga High School.jpg\n | image_size              = 250px\n | caption                 = Conestoga High School in 2006\n | motto                   = A Tradition of Excellence\n | address                 = 200 Irish Rd\n | city                    = [[Berwyn, Pennsylvania|Berwyn]]\n | state                   = Pennsylvania\n | zipcode                 = 19312\n | country                 = United States\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|40.0472|-75.4533|format=dms|type:edu_region:US-PA|display=inline,title}}\n | pushpin_map             = USA Pennsylvania#USA\n | pushpin_map_caption     = Location of school in Pennsylvania\n | other_names             = Conestoga Senior High School, CHS\n | nickname                = Stoga\n | former_name             = Tredyffrin Easttown High School\n | type                    = [[Comprehensive high school|Comprehensive public high school]]\n | established             = {{Start date and age|1954|10|27}}\n | opened                  = {{Start date and age|1955|09|09}}\n | district                = [[Tredyffrin/Easttown School District|Tredyffrin/Easttown]]\n | superintendent          = Richard Gusick\n | ceeb                    = 390295\n | us_nces_district_id     = {{NCES District ID|4223640|district_name= Tredyffrin-Easttown SD|access_date=5 March 2019}}\n | us_nces_school_id       = {{NCES School ID|422364001423|school_name= Conestoga SHS|access_date=5 March 2019}}\n | principal               = Dr. Amy Meisinger\n | teaching_staff          = 137.10 {{FTE}}\n | grades                  = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n | enrollment              = 2,141\n | enrollment_as_of        = 2016-2017\n | ratio                   = 15.62\n | campus_type             = [[Suburban]]\n | USNWR_ranking           = 378th\n | national_ranking        = [http://www.newsweek.com/high-schools/americas-top-high-schools-2016 36th (Newsweek)]<br>\n[https://k12.niche.com/d/tredyffrin-easttown-school-district-pa/ 1st (Niche School District Ranking)]\n | colors                  = Garnet and Gray {{Color box|Maroon}}{{Color box|Gray}}\n | mascot                  = [[American pioneer|The Pioneer]]\n | rival                   = \n | newspaper               = {{URL|http://spoke.news|The Spoke}}\n | yearbook                = {{URL|http://stogayearbook.com|The Pioneer}}\n | feeder_schools          = {{hlist|Tredyffrin Easttown Middle School|Valley Forge Middle School}}\n | website                 = {{URL|http://tesd.net/stoga|Conestoga Homepage}}\n | footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Conestoga High School''', located in [[Tredyffrin Township, Pennsylvania|Tredyffrin Township]],<ref>\"[http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=06000US4202977344&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on Tredyffrin township, Chester County, Pennsylvania]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" ''[[U.S. Census Bureau]]''. Retrieved on May 26, 2009.</ref> [[Pennsylvania]], United States, is the only [[high school|upper secondary school]] in the [[Tredyffrin/Easttown School District]].\n\nConestoga, commonly referred to as \"Stoga,\" is {{convert|20|mi|km}} northwest of [[Philadelphia]] in the suburbs known as the [[Pennsylvania Main Line|Main Line]].\n\n==College and university matriculation==\n\n<!-- The point of listing matriculation is to show the high-achievement of graduates. Therefore, it is not necessary to list every single school with 1+ enrollment. -->\n\n97% of Conestoga graduates advance to colleges and universities, 92% of them to four-year colleges and universities. Graduating classes from 2009 to 2014 sent one or more students to each of the [[Ivy League]] colleges, [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Duke University]], [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[University of Chicago]], [[The California Institute of Technology]], and [[Carnegie Mellon University]].  The most popular university choice for Conestoga students is [[Pennsylvania State University]]. The second most popular choice is the [[University of Pittsburgh]]. Fifty-two percent of Conestoga students leave Pennsylvania to attend colleges and universities, and more than 52% attend private institutions after graduation.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web |url=http://www.tesd.k12.pa.us/stoga/profile.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060208234102/http://www.tesd.k12.pa.us/stoga/profile.pdf |archivedate=February 8, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Departments==\n\nConestoga has eight academic departments: Business/Technology, English, World Languages, Mathematics, Science, Social Studies, Visual and Performing Arts, and Wellness/Fitness/Family & Consumer Science. Students must earn 24 credits in order to graduate. 1 credit is equivalent to a year-long class.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Distinctions and honors==\n\nIn 2012 Conestoga was ranked the 180th best high school in the country and 1st in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|title=America's Best High Schools|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/05/20/america-s-best-high-schools.html|access-date=October 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521045950/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/05/20/america-s-best-high-schools.html|archive-date=May 21, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Conestoga was ranked 312th (3rd in Pennsylvania) in 2008, 301st (3rd in Pennsylvania) in 2007, 170th (1st in Pennsylvania) in 2006,<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/12532678?s=100&np=12&sort=raa The 1,200 Top U.S. Schools \u2013 Newsweek America's Best High Schools \u2013 MSNBC.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205210048/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/12532678?s=100&np=12&sort=raa |date=February 5, 2007 }}</ref> 195th in 2005,<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/7723397/site/newsweek/page/2/ The 1,200 Top U.S. Schools \u2013 Newsweek America's Best High Schools \u2013 MSNBC.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061115235931/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/7723397/site/newsweek/page/2/ |date=November 15, 2006 }}</ref> and 197th in 2003.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/6362098/site/newsweek/page/2/ 2003 List: The Top High Schools \u2013 Newsweek America's Best High Schools \u2013 MSNBC.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419230509/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/6362098/site/newsweek/page/2/ |date=April 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Niche.com ranked the Tredyffrin Easttown school district number one in the USA. In the 2016 edition of Newsweek's \"America's Top High Schools,\" Conestoga High School was ranked 36th in the nation and the 1st in Pennsylvania.<ref>http://www.newsweek.com/high-schools/americas-top-high-schools-2016</ref> For the 2012\u20132013 school year the school was ranked as a Gold Medal School by U.S. News & World Report, ranked number 313 nationally.<ref name=\"Best High Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://education.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-high-schools/listings/pennsylvania/conestoga-high-school|title=Best High Schools|work=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[U.S. News and World Report]] consistently includes Conestoga High School in their annual list of America's \"Best High Schools.\"  U.S. News & World Report ranked Conestoga as a Gold Medal High School, the 313th of America's for 2010\u20132011.<ref name=\"Best High Schools\"/>\n\n===SAT===\n\nThe Conestoga Class of 2014 performed at least 94 points above the national average in every section of the SAT:<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Test Type\n! National Average\n! Conestoga\n|-\n| '''Reading'''\n| 497\n| 598\n|-\n| '''Math'''\n| 513\n| 607\n|-\n| '''Writing'''\n| 487\n| 590\n|}\nCompared to all the other schools in Chester County, Conestoga had the highest average SAT score in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/pennsylvania/te/heres-how-conestoga-high-school-did-2019-sats|title=Here's How Conestoga High School Did On The 2019 SATs|date=2020-02-21|website=Tredyffrin-Easttown, PA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===National Merit/College Board Recognition===\n\nThe Conestoga Class of 2018 includes 34 National Merit Semifinalists, 26 National Merit Commended Students, and 2 National Hispanic Scholars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesd.net/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=78&ModuleInstanceID=2449&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=32392&PageID=351|title=In the News - Detail Page|website=tesd.net|language=en|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> The Conestoga Class of 2009 includes 21 National Merit Semifinalists, 35 National Merit Commended Students, 1 National Achievement Scholar, and 1 National Hispanic Scholar award recipients.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Advanced Placement Program===\n\nIn May 2008, 573 Conestoga students, or 30% of the student body, took 1,103 College Board Advanced Placement (AP) examinations. A score of 3 or higher was earned on 95% of the tests.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe [[Siemens Foundation]] for Advanced Placement honored Conestoga thrice, with the 2009 Student Award, 2006\u201307 High School Award, and 2005\u201306 Student Award. This program highlights exceptional achievement in science, mathematics, and technology.<ref>[http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/SAAP2005_06winners.pdf 2006 Siemens Awards for AP Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091115144736/http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/SAAP2005_06winners.pdf |date=November 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/2006_07APAwardWinners.pdf 2007 Siemens Awards for AP Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021123423/http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/2006_07APAwardWinners.pdf |date=October 21, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/word_listing_of_2009_saap_winners.pdf 2009 Siemens Awards for AP Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326063759/http://www.siemens-foundation.org/pool/advanced_placement/word_listing_of_2009_saap_winners.pdf |date=March 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Pennsylvania System of School Assessment===\n\nConestoga performs well on the [[Pennsylvania System of School Assessment]] (PSSA). The average scaled scores for Conestoga were among the highest in the state in 2008.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Test Type\n! State\n! Conestoga\n|-\n| '''Reading'''\n| 1470\n| 1680\n|-\n| '''Math'''\n| 1360\n| 1600\n|-\n| '''Writing'''\n| 1340\n| 1600\n|}\n\n==Spoke News==\n{{POV|date=February 2013}}\nConestoga is home to a student-produced news website, [http://spoke.news Spoke.news] (formerly Stoganews.com). It is produced by the staff of ''The Spoke,'' Conestoga's student run newspaper, and TETV. Spoke.news has been the recipient of several national awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mainlinemedianews.com/mainlinesuburbanlife/news/conestoga-students-win-national-journalism-award/article_91235ff4-0bfb-5601-ac60-ef6f6a3f4aaa.html|title=Conestoga students win national journalism award|last=GLASGOWbglasgow@journalregister.com|first=BRENT|website=Main Line Media News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n\n=== STEM Programs ===\nConestoga's science department has numerous [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] clubs and activities. Among them are [[Science Olympiad]], chemistry, biology, computer science, and robotics.\n\n=== Academic Competitions ===\nConestoga is a part of Chester County Academic Competition league, the [[DECA (organization)|DECA]] business competition, as well as at the Pennsylvania State Career Development Conference.\n\n=== Civic Engagement ===\nIn 2017, Conestoga was the first high school to receive the Pennsylvania Governor's Civic Engagement Award for registering 85% of eligible students to vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mainlinemedianews.com/lifestyle/conestoga-high-school-s-new-voters-club-honored-with-civic-engagement-award/article_dedb2e0d-762e-551b-9570-288204479f01.html|title=Conestoga High School\u2019s New Voters Club honored with Civic Engagement Award|website=Main Line Media News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pennsylvania-department-of-state-honored-conestoga-high-school-for-voter-registration-achievement-300564613.html|title=Pennsylvania Department of State Honored Conestoga High School for Voter Registration Achievement|last=State|first=Pennsylvania Department of|website=prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/pennsylvania/te/conestoga-new-voters-club-earns-governors-civic-engagement-award|title=Conestoga New Voters Club Earns Governor's Civic Engagement Award|date=2017-12-01|website=Tredyffrin-Easttown, PA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> In 2018, the students who ran the drive brought the organization {{Cite web|url=https://new-voters.org|title=New Voters}} to the national level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/news/weare18-conestoga-high-school-vote-2018-new-voters-20180405.html|title=These Philly-area teens got 100 classmates to register to vote. Now, they're taking the next step|last=Orso|first=Anna|website=https://www.inquirer.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Athletic teams===\nConestoga competes in 17 different sporting events generally within the [[Central League (PIAA)|Central League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piaa.org/schools/directory/details.aspx?ID=11033|title=PIAA \u2013 Schools \u2013 Directory \u2013 Conestoga High School|work=piaa.org}}</ref>\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\"\n!      !!  Male  !! Female !!width=\"50\"|\n!      !!  Male  !! Female !!width=\"50\"|\n!      !!  Male  !! Female\n|-\n! Fall\n| Cross Country || Cross Country || <!--1st row of Fall-->\n! Winter\n| Basketball || Basketball || <!--1st row of Winter-->\n! Spring\n| Baseball || Softball <!--1st row of Spring-->\n|-\n!\n| Football || Field Hockey || <!-- 2nd row of Fall -->\n!\n| Swimming || Swimming || <!-- 2nd row of Winter -->\n!\n| Lacrosse || Lacrosse <!-- 2nd row of Spring -->\n|-\n!\n| Golf || Golf ||\n!\n| Indoor Track || Indoor Track ||\n!\n| Track || Track\n|-\n!\n| Soccer || Soccer ||\n!\n| Wrestling || Cheerleading ||\n!\n| Tennis ||\n|-\n!\n|  || Tennis ||\n!\n|  ||  ||\n!\n|  ||\n|-\n!\n|  || Volleyball ||\n!\n|  ||  ||\n!\n|  ||\n|-\n!\n|  || Cheerleading ||\n!\n|  ||  ||\n!\n|  ||\n|}\n\n===Athletic clubs===\n\n====Fall====\n*Ice Hockey\n*Ultimate Frisbee\n*Cross Country\n*Volleyball\n*Sailing\n\n====Winter====\n* Ice Hockey\n* Squash\n\n====Spring====\n*Crew\n*Rugby (Conestoga boasts the oldest High School Rugby program in the United States \u2013 founded in 1971 by Clarence Culpepper who played for and coached the US National Men's Team.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mainlinetoday.com/core/pagetools.php?pageid=6028&url=%2FMain-Line-Today%2FApril-2007%2FFRONTLINE-Neighborhood%2F&mode=print|title=- FRONTLINE: Neighborhood|work=mainlinetoday.com}}</ref>\n*Ultimate Frisbee\n*Sailing\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{More citations needed section|date=November 2012}} \n*[[Elizabeth Hoffman (professor)|Elizabeth Hoffman]] \u2013 1964. Executive vice-president, Iowa State University, president emerita, University of Colorado System.\n*[[Craig Lucas]] \u2013 1969.  Tony-award nominated American playwright.\n*[[Johanna Schmitt]] \u2013 1970. Distinguished Professor of Evolution and Ecology, [[University of California, Davis]]; Stephen T. Olney Professor of Natural History and Harrison S. Kravis University Professor, [[Brown University]].\n*[[Robert Ellis (author)|Robert Ellis]] -1972. LA Times Bestselling Author.\n*[[Grant Shaud]] \u2013 1979. Actor.\n*[[Todd Glass]] \u2013 1982. Comedian, actor.\n*[[Glenn R. Simpson]] - 1982. Journalist.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/us/politics/fusion-gps-glenn-simpson.html</ref>\n*[[Melissa Shusterman]] -1985. Member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]].\n*[[Drew Endy]] \u2013 1988. Bioengineering professor at [[Stanford University]], founder of the [[Registry of Standard Biological Parts]].\n*[[Gregg Foreman]] - 1990. Musician and Actor.\n*[[Jennie Eisenhower]] \u2013 1996. Actress, granddaughter of President [[Richard Nixon]] and great-granddaughter of President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].\n*[[Dave Bush|David Bush]] \u2013 1998. Professional baseball player.\n*[[Marquis Weeks]] \u2013 2000. Professional football player.\n*[[Abbi Jacobson]] \u2013 2002. Actress and co-creator of [[Comedy Central]] television series [[Broad City]].\n*[[Pat Heim]] \u2013 2003. College lacrosse All-America Penn State '07, #1 overall pick Major League Lacrosse 2007 Draft player.\n*[[Kasie Hunt]] - 2003. Political correspondent.\n*[[Chris Hurst (Virginia politician)|Chris Hurst]] - 2005. Former TV Anchor and member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]].\n*[[P.T. Ricci]] \u2013 2005. [[Major League Lacrosse]] player.\n*[[Mark Herzlich]] \u2013 2006. Professional football player.\n*[[Mt. Joy (band)|Mt. Joy]] - Indie folk/rock band featuring Matt Quinn (2009) and Sam Cooper (2007).\n*[[Roger Hobbs]] -2007. International bestselling author of the books ''Ghostman'' and ''Vanishing Games''.\n*[[Emma Boettcher]] - 2010. Champion on [[Jeopardy!]].\n*[[Christine Fan]] \u2013 Singer and actress.\n*[[Brian Chippendale]] \u2013 [[rock (music)|Rock]] drummer and vocalist.\n*[[Keith Hughes (baseball)|Keith Hughes]] \u2014 former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher (1987\u201388; '90, '93)\n*[[Tommy Shields]] \u2014 former [[Chicago Cubs]] infielder\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tesd.net/stoga Conestoga's homepage]\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20100612035013/http://tesd.net/stoga/profile.pdf School profile]\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20100612034448/http://tesd.net/Publications/pos.pdf Program of Studies]\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20100612035227/http://tesd.net/menus/CHS.pdf Lunch Menu]\n**[https://archive.is/20050209120045/http://www.tesd.net/District/schools.htm District Schools]\n*[http://www.tesd.net/ T/E School District homepage]\n*[http://www.conestogabaseball.com Conestoga Baseball]\n*[http://www.conestogagirlslacrosse.com/ Conestoga Girls' Lacrosse]\n*[http://conestogasoccer.com/ Conestoga Boys' Soccer]\n*[http://www.pioneerwrestling.com/ Conestoga Wrestling]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930002204/http://stogatrackxc.com/ Conestoga Cross Country and Track and Field]\n*[http://stogamusic.com/ 'Stoga Music Department]\n*[http://spoke.news/ 'Spoke News]\n*[http://stogayearbook.com/ 'Stoga Yearbook]\n\n{{Tredyffrin Township, Chester County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Chester County, Pennsylvania School Districts}}\n{{Pennsylvania Central League High Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Main Line]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Eastern Pennsylvania Rugby Union]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Schools in Chester County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{peacock|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Conestoga High School\n | seal_image              = StogaLogo.png\n | seal_size               = \n | image                   = Conestoga High School.jpg\n | image_size              = 250px\n | caption                 = Cones